The Sacred Four - Re-awakening Ancestral Ways of Knowing. The project is a way of bringing our communities together to bring awareness about the true history of Indian residential schools. We gather to walk, eat, learn, and heal together in a good way. Especially for all our residential school survivors. It's purpose is to re-awaken ancestral ways of knowing and relearning natural laws such as rewakening our nehiyawak (Cree) language and ancestral culture, heritage, and reconnecting to our natural world.

Pastor Ohm Pokachom has a house church in Calgary under the name of Calgary Church of Living Waters.  He has been coming up to the Lacombe area to help with an outreach here in our area for the last few years.   We are working with him in establishing a church amongst the Thai here in our area.  He is training the new Christians and training leaders within their group.  The main use of the finances that we provide to him is for transportation from Calgary.  He makes the trip every second week.  We have also worked with him to hold 2 outreaches over the past year, one at Easter and the second at Christmas.  I was asked to speak at those outreaches and shared the good news of Jesus with them, with Pastor Ohm acting as my translator to Thai language.    Meet with Pastor Ohm via phone at least quarterly to be kept up to date on current activities.

The Helper will work with the Elders to build the organization s strategy and vision, be responsible for the day-to-day operation of the organization including the development of an annual fundraising strategy, and the development of partnerships. They will also serve as a key spokesperson for the organization, articulating its mission, vision, and impact to diverse audiences.

Deliver a food hamper program in our neighbourhood: Every Thursday, the NPNA puts together free, weekly grocery hampers that go out to about 100 households per week, representing about 260 individuals. Hamper recipients live in the North Park neighbourhood. The hampers are made up of produce, bread, dairy, and non-perishable items. Volunteers from the Emmaus Community and Abbey Church participate in this program. Participant feedback highlighted the vital role the program played in alleviating food insecurity, especially amid rising grocery costs. Many respondents described the hampers as  immensely helpful  noting the positive impact on both nutrition and mental wellbeing.   The program also fostered meaningful collaboration between local organizations and the business community, strengthening neighbourhood-level relationships. In addition to food distribution, the program created part-time paid employment opportunities for both youth and seniors, while also providing volunteer roles.

Green Ummah is a Canadian non-profit that aims to raise environmental and social justice awareness within the Muslim community. Founded by youth advocates, it has grown to include a diverse team and volunteer base. In partnership with Nature Canada, the organization has hosted Canada's first Muslim-organized environmental conference and developed the "Greening our Communities Toolkit," a curriculum focused on environmental justice. Initially launched in five classes, the toolkit has expanded to 25, reaching beyond the Muslim community to engage racialized and newcomer students. The program has revealed a high demand for education on environmental racism in Ontario schools and uncovered a lack of nature engagement among marginalized students. The grant will fund curriculum updates, teacher training, and program expansion.

The Serdachny Elevate Foundation ( SEF ) is a not-for-profit organization registered under the Societies Act of Alberta. The mission of SEF is to support healthy, active living through sport, education and life; supporting kids, youth, adults, organizations and communities to elevate and succeed in life.  This is achieved through providing educational scholarships, sport support, and sport programming to communities.  Funds distributed through SEF will support programming and individual awards and bursaries related to its mission. This may include things like: reimbursement for sport and recreation registration fees; educational awards in recognition of health philanthropy and volunteerism; sports program funding; and financial support for children s health-related costs not covered by other means.  All funds distributed will meet the requirements of being related to health and benefiting children and youth (under age 18) in Alberta.

The Steinert & Ferreiro Award celebrates individuals who, through either the arts or sciences, made a significant contribution to the understanding and acceptance of gays and lesbians in the community. An individual will be presented with $15,000. Cheryl Dobinson honoured for 25+ years of contributions to 2SLGBTQ+ communities, particularly focusing on bi+ and youth. Cheryl is an activist, researcher, and mentor, who has tackled homophobia, biphobia, and transphobia while creating spaces for support and celebration. Her career includes extensive work in community health, volunteerism, and research, with notable roles at Planned Parenthood Toronto, Pride Toronto, and the University of Toronto. Cheryl s work spans leadership in 2SLGBTQ+ programming, advocacy for trans inclusion, bisexual health research, and education. She has co-authored over 20 academic papers, led training initiatives, and been a voice for bi+ communities in policy discussions, including at the White House.

AstroSankofa Arts Initiatives brings forward more opportunities and production for Black creatives and youth who work within the realms of Black science and speculative fiction in addition to the five dimensions of Afrofuturism (2.0): metaphysics, aesthetics, theoretical and applied sciences, social science and programmatic spaces. The initiatives include but are not limited to the curation and production of exhibitions, public art installation productions, conventions and panels, and Web3 interventions such as nonfungible token projects and metaverse expeditions. Each initiative will reinstate the power of arts and the Black community's connection to their ancestral roots to improve the future.

Grant Recipient Name: The Chinese Canadian National Council Toronto Chapter
Grant Purpose: The Chinese Canadian National Council Toronto Chapter (CCNCTO) is an organization made up of Chinese Canadians in the Greater Toronto Area (GTA). CCNCTO promotes equity, social justice, inclusive civic participation, and respect for diversity. The three pillars of our work include 1) serving marginalized Chinese community members who face multiple barriers in accessing existing resources, 2) developing and delivering culturally and language accessible anti-racism community resources and workshops, and 3) engaging in policy advocacy to promote equity, antiracism, and human rights. School based agricultural education projects in two villages in North Eastern Zambia - Chinema and Samafunda.  The funding supports agricultural inputs including seed, livestock, veterinary medicines, fertilizer, tree stock, fencing and well maintenance at the schools.    What started as small, locally driven educational initiatives has now grown into government-supported institutions, securing long-term sustainability for both education and agriculture.   Chinema is now home to over 500 students, more than half of whom are girls. With 10 dedicated teachers, the school boasts thriving agricultural projects including guava and orange orchards, livestock, and gardens that feed both the students and the wider community.   Samafunda supports 246 students and 10 educators, and its agricultural efforts   from eggplants to goats   are helping to nourish the community and build local capacity.

Address food sovereignty and food security issues, and Food First NL s new province-wide Lived/Living Experience Advisory Group  This grant will empower individuals facing food insecurity with knowledge of how the emergency food system operates, how it could be better, and the tools to engage with it. This project aligns with Food First NL s overall approach to educational and outreach initiatives, which is focused on creating space for and valuing community-level insights into our food system as a way of enabling action. They have a long history of leading community-led food assessments, hosting hands-on food skills workshops, and creating opportunities for intergenerational learning around food.

This project will build community-based infrastructure to make fresh, local food more accessible in Newfoundland and Labrador particularly in rural communities, where barriers to food access are at their highest.  Many Newfoundlanders and Labradorians, particularly rural ones, face geographical and logistical barriers to accessing the food they would like to eat. Even with adequate income, food access can be very limited for people who don t have access to a vehicle or to the very substantial time and money needed to travel to a large centre. Access to the freshest local food is often even more difficult, with a distributed and often difficult-to-find network of producers.

Building on already-approved funding from the Government of NL, this grant will enable Food First NL to lead a comprehensive and collaborative consultation process that will inform recommendations for the timely roll-out of a universal school food program in Newfoundland and Labrador. It will also allow Food First NL to fully participate in school food advocacy, programming, and funding efforts led by national partners, building capacity and connections more broadly for Newfoundland and Labrador.

Objective 1: Facilitate a planning process to co-design tangible community-led plans and actions to advance food sovereignty with Indigenous, Black, and racialized communities across Canada.   Objective 2: Build relationships across communities and contexts to strengthen networks and identify core challenges and actionable opportunities to advance food sovereignty   Objective 3: Harness and share cross-cultural knowledge and strategies to increase capacity to advance food sovereignty and build capacity and increased access to resources for the most disenfranchised communities in the food systems.

Essentially this program is built on the idea that as a community, we feel better and do better when we are united together. Building connections are essential to us all and are a protective factor not only against isolation and loneliness but also towards anything we are struggling with. Connectivity to each other and our community can help to bridge gaps, create conversation and root us together to make us stronger. And with the ongoing daily struggle our students and community face we strongly believe that enhancing these connections will also help reduce bullying, anxiety, fear and the feeling of depression many of us are feeling. The power of connectivity and conversation is powerful and when utilized/practiced it will vastly help our students and our community members. The Consecon Foundation made 5 grants, totalling $167,766 ($10,000 in Jan 2024, $15,000 in Feb 2024, $50,000 in Aug 2024, $50,000 in Aug 2024, and $42,766 in Dec 2024).   The Jan and Feb grants facilitated a strategic planning exercise in Montreal, including a tour of a cell culture manufacturing facility and a networking event for the Montreal cellular agriculture community.  The grants in Aug 2024 were the interim and final payments for a grant agreement signed in Dec 2023, to -Support Cellular Agriculture Canada (CAC) activities and costs associated with the organization -Convene meetings with provincial and federal officials and other parties -Prepare other funding proposals and support cellular agriculture research  The Dec 2024 grant covered strategic planning and community building work in Edmonton in September 2024, including: the second gathering of CAC, and an international conference bringing together 20 international leaders in cellular agriculture.

The Consecon Foundation made a three-year, $150,000 funding commitment to Ontario Genomics to support cellular agriculture initiatives in Ontario from 2024-26. We believe Ontario Genomics' work will help Canada create a more sustainable food system, which will support the foundation's work in one of its key program areas: accelerating the protein transition.   The first year of the program focused on the development & preparation of a follow-up report to Ontario Genomics' groundbreaking 2021 report on cellular agriculture in Canada. The grant supported research for the revised report as well as costs of report launch and communications. The report was launched in March 2025 and can be found here: https://www.ontariogenomics.ca/canada-synbio-2024-unlocking-the-future/  The foundation also made a grant of $10,000 to support Ontario Genomics' Canada Synbio 2024 conference. More information can be found here: https://www.ontariogenomics.ca/canada-synbio-2024

L'année 2024 a été la deuxième année d'un partenariat de 20,000$ par année sur trois ans avec l'école primaire et secondaire à Gracefield. La région de la Haute-Gatineau est parmi les plus désavantagée socio-économiquement au Québec, et l'objectif de notre partenariat est d'aider les jeunes du secondaire de persévérer dns leurs études secondaires et de graduer. Donc, notre soutien financier à l'école essaie de contrer  la pauvreté par l'aide alimentaire, des trousses d'hygiène, des incitatifs de motivation et des bourses de persévérance et de succès. Nos partenaires à l'école ont préparé un Bilan 2024 (ci-joint à ce rapport), avec une description détaillé des activités du partenariat et des dépenses faites  en 2024. Notre propre revue diligente des activités et dépenses de 2024 nous ont fait clairement fait  conclure que ces activités et dépenses ont été faits pour des raisons caritatives.

The purpose of this grant is to fulfill several needs in Kathmandu, Nepal. It aims to relieve poverty by providing essential humanitarian assistance to individuals in need. Additionally, it seeks to offer comprehensive support, including counselling, education, food, clothing, and shelter, to those affected by violence and human trafficking. Another fulfilled need is to advance education by offering scholarships, bursaries, awards, and other forms of financial assistance to students in need, enabling them to attend schools, colleges, and universities that provide degree courses and trades programs. The grant also focuses on developing and implementing educational programs designed to raise awareness about human trafficking and offer effective prevention strategies. It provides vocational training programs that equip individuals with skills for long-term employment. Lastly, we collaborate with local organizations to create sustainable solutions for preventing human trafficking.

Dans le cadre du fonds Agri-Esprit de Financement agricole Canada (FAC), Protec-Terre a obtenue une subvention pour aménager des infrastructures sur le site de la fiducie d'utilité sociale Akwekon Nici vouée  à la sécurité alimentaire de la communauté. Ces fonds ont été transféré à l'OBNL Cercle culturel Lusekut tel que prévu dans l'entente avec FAC. Les fonds ont servi à l'achat de matériaux (bois, transport, recouvrement) pour la fabrication d'une serre, l'achat d'un tracteur usagé  et d'un rotoculteur, et de bacs pour plantations et d'outillage de jardinage. Il y a aussi eu de la formation en écoconstruction et services conseils en agroforesterie pour les bénéficiaires.

L'APBVAL est un partenaire de Protec-Terre dans le cadre de la création d'une fiducie d'utilité sociale agroécologique (FUSA) dans la région de Sherbrooke. Les fonds servent aux démarches administratives et juridiques liées à la création de la FUSA. La mission de Protec-Terre étant de préserver les terres en culture agroécologique au bénéfice de la communauté en faisant avancer les connaissances pour l'industrie agricole, ce projet entre dans le cadre de notre mission.

Building the Circle - Creating Systemic Pathways for HIV/viral hepatitis services - Building the Circle initiative will establish a process whereby Indigenous community members in Toronto will have increased knowledge and access to Point-of-Care (POC) testing and treatment for HIV and viral hepatitis.

There is no Indigenous word for HCV !   Incorporating Cultural and Traditional Experiences to Shape and Change HCV Testing in the Piikani Nation. This initiative will first build relationship with the Piikani Nation to create a safe space for members to share their experiences and reflections regarding hepatitis C (HCV). We will incorporate the teachings from our relationship building into materials used in DBS training and testing including video, manuals, concepts, test results, etc into a form that reflects the traditional and cultural values and (Blackfoot) language of the Piikani Nation. Many teachings are oral in nature, therefore efforts will also be made to capture these learnings so they are not lost. Teachings will explain the colonial origin of HCV and the resulting harm that has led to an over-representation of Indigenous peoples with HCV infection.

This project addresses multiple barriers through access to agriculture-related, land-based, Indigenous led, culturally safe education and barrier support services such as: Employment and apprenticeship opportunities; Indigenous agriculture and food sovereignty education and training services; Cultural and mental health supports; Community food distribution: Producing culturally appropriate foods for free community distribution, as well as seeds, food plants, and root stock; Provision of transportation; Provision of accommodation and housing; Provision of clothing, safety equipment, and tools. The objective of this project is to support the revitalization of the culture of economic interdependence and food production that was a central part of life for Indigenous peoples in Northwestern BC.

This project involves a sector analysis of the small-scale poultry sector in BC. The analysis will provide an invaluable lens through which to view the dynamics, challenges, and opportunities facing these producers. This analysis, crucial for stakeholders across the entire agricultural landscape, aims to inform future policy-making, guide sustainable practices, and identify growth avenues within the sector. While speci cally focusing on the Southern Interior of BC as the target location, the analysis caters to the growing and unmet demand for ethical, sustainable, and locally sourced food options.

These may take place at the farm or virtually, as dictated by public health guidelines and any logistical needs dictated by the partner. Grant Recipient Name: Good Food Box Society of North Okanagan
Grant Purpose: As part of our charitable purposes, we support The Good Food Box Society. These qualifying disbursements were to provide funding to strengthen the local food system by increasing access to regional produce for seniors and low income families. This funding will provide 150 large produce boxes a month through local schools and seniors' organizations to families and seniors in need. This funding will help GFB to: build a new website to increase access to the food boxes by enabling recipients to order online; hire a digital assistant to train staff, volunteers, customers and agencies to learn new digital ordering skills; and strategize to be more efficient and accessible.

Grant Recipient Name: ROYAL REGIMENT OF CANADA REGIMENTAL FUND

Grant Purpose: Distribution of 1050 care packages for unhoused community members in collaboration with students from Comox Valley schools. Care packages include homemade holiday cards, cookies, warm socks, toques, mitts, scarves and toiletries. Participating students learn about community leadership, rehumanizing homelessness, addiction, compassion, local poverty, project management, marketing, self-care in service, gratitude and being changemakers. Care packages were distributed at 16 local Comox Valley support agencies, shelters and soup kitchens.

Funding for direct support services for Indigenous people who are unhoused or at risk of unhoused. Current client base is the urban Indigenous population with an emphasis on women, youth, and two spirit individuals. The majority of these clients are living in Courtenay's downtown core. Support services include advocacy, assisting with housing searches/applications and support with maintaining housing. A portion of this funding was also used for emergency needs for unhoused individuals such as equipment (tents, sleeping bags, hygiene, etc), and transportation needs.

Funding for weekly meal service on Sundays in the Comox Valley, serving 70+ clients a week. The unhoused population relies on the meal program on Sundays to ensure they are fed a well nutritious and consistent meal. Clients can also access harm reduction supplies, donated clothing items, water, naloxone training, blankets, toiletries, tents and blankets. The unhoused community thrives off the connection with others at this program, and it helps to encourage the use of resources within the Comox Valley. Funding is primarily for food costs as well as program expenses.

Grant Recipient Name: Oromian Centre Hope Foundation of Alberta
Grant Purpose: The project aims to enhance the use of English language among East Africans to address their low English literacy & proficiency. By expanding OCHFA s English Language Proficiency (ELP) program, this will improve East Africans  communication in English, thereby creating employment opportunities to help reduce financial barriers, improving access to social programs & strengthening connections to improve their well-being. This grant enables OCHFA to expand its ELP & reach more East Africans.

Komkan is looking to provide mental health support for the south sudanese and african community to overcome preimmigration trauma through use of researched and Trauma Informed Culturally Sensitive practice. Our approach incorporates various competencies, such as the African form of psychotherapy, as well as evidence-based practices derived from theories like cognitive behavior therapy, narrative exposure therapy, and solution-focused therapy.
This grant is to support the general charitable activity of the Komkan Africa Institute.
